{"summary":"All four amendments have technical merit: one is a safe observability improvement, one exposes a real crash-consistency gap across durable writes, and two identify backward-compatibility defects in legacy task-run lineage handling.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-2-0432d582","decision":"accept","rationale":"In the exact-`run_id` path, the code has already identified a specific entry before hitting the terminal-state guard, but the resulting error omits that discriminator. Including `run={run_id}` is a safe, consistent diagnostic improvement that makes duplicate-finalization failures materially easier to debug."},{"amendment_id":"fr-2-95143b50","decision":"accept","rationale":"`service::update_task_run` persists lineage, snapshot, and journal as separate durable operations with no transaction or recovery step spanning them. A crash after the lineage write can leave snapshot counters and journal state stale while the lineage entry is already terminal, so documenting the failure mode and/or providing reconciliation from lineage is justified."},{"amendment_id":"fr-2-31529cd0","decision":"accept","rationale":"The legacy format stored one attempt as a `running` row plus a later terminal row, and the current `find_runs_for_bead` implementation only filters and sorts raw rows. That means historical attempts can be returned twice and still appear to have an in-flight `running` record, which is a real backward-compatibility bug and needs regression coverage."},{"amendment_id":"fr-2-babd2df3","decision":"accept","rationale":"When `run_id` is absent, the updater treats every non-terminal row for the same `bead_id` and `project_id` as an open attempt. On legacy data, completed attempts leave behind their original `running` start rows, so a later retry in the same project can be misclassified as ambiguous and incorrectly rejected; those legacy pairs need to be ignored or normalized, with a test covering the case."}]}